[1] Cholera - Uganda (Kampala)
Date: Fri, 15 Dec 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The Monitor (Kampala) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200612150031.html>

The number of cholera cases in the city has risen from 305 last week to 511
at the moment in the 5 divisions of Kampala. This was revealed by the
city's director of health services, Mesach Mubiru on yesterday, 14 Dec 2006.
Dr Mubiru and a team of health inspectors that included representatives
from the WHO, Uganda Red cross, Ministry of Health, Plan Uganda, National
Water and Sewerage Corporation, and UNICEF were going around the city
sensitizing people on how to promote personal hygiene and prevent
themselves from contracting cholera while providing patients with oral
rehydration salts.
"People should only take boiled water, use latrines well and wash hands
with soap before and after meals, eat only properly prepared food and
report any cholera cases immediately," he said. In the process, the team
led by Dr Mubiru and the town clerk Ms Ruth Kijambu closed 8 residential
and commercial buildings in Kawempe Lubaga and Makindye divisions due to
poor sanitation.
Houses in Kinyogoga, an area in Namuwongo, Makindye division, Nateete in
Lubaga and Kawempe division were closed because they lacked proper latrine
facilities. Dr Mubiru said KCC would continue closing houses with poor
sanitation to check the spread of cholera, which has has taken root in the
city.
Kawempe division health inspector, David Katwere, attributed the cholera
outbreak in Bwaise, Karerwe, Nsooba and other slums to the practice of
emptying pit latrines in flooded water channels during the rainy season.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
