[2] Cholera - Uganda ex Sudan
Date: Wed, 13 Dec 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The Monitor (Kampala) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200612131199.html>

Two cholera victims were flown in from Sudan yesterday, 12 Dec 2006. The
Ugandan women were employed in Sudan. Josephine Muwanguzi, a nurse at the
cholera camp at Mulago Hospital, said a test confirmed they had cholera.
However, one of them was discharged in the morning. The resident of Ntinda,
a city suburb, said she worked as a bar attendant in a hotel. "I have been
working for Civicon Oasis Hotel in Sudan for 7 months. The hotel paid for
my transport from Sudan to Kampala," Nakandi said.
She said the hotel management decided to bring her back to Uganda for
treatment when her situation became worse.
Winnie Bukenya, a senior nurse at the cholera camp, disclosed that the
number of patients had risen to 509 from 463, but the death toll remained at 5.
******
[3] Cholera - Uganda
Date: Wed, 13 Dec 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The Monitor (Kampala) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200612130178.html>

Over 92 people have died of cholera nationwide in the last 12 months, the
Ministry of Health update on the epidemic has revealed.
In November 2006, 12 deaths occurred as a total of 508 cases were recorded.
In October 2006, 13 deaths were recorded out of 408 cases. So far, in
December 2006, there were at least 3 fatalities out of 142 cases.
The report entitled "status of cholera outbreak in Uganda" captures
reported and confirmed cases across the country from Jan to Dec 2006. It
puts the national accumulative figure of cases at 4386 with Kitgum, at 1460
and Kampala, at 463, currently the most affected districts.
By press time, the death toll in Kampala had increased to 5 over the
weekend. Kitgum had recorded 23 deaths. Other districts hit hardest by the
epidemic in the earlier months include Bundibugyo (611), Arua (343),
Adjumani (235), Kasese (212), Koboko (231), Moyo (216), Hoima (170),
Masindi (132), Nebbi (134), Pader (130), and Yumbe (128).
******
[4] Cholera - Angola (Benguela)
Date: Fri, 15 Dec 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Government of Angola [edited]
<http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/VBOL-6WHHG3?OpenDocument>

At least 4 people have died from cholera in the past 24 hours in Ganda
district, southern Benguela province. With these deaths the number rises to
7, from 67 cases notified since 6 Dec 2006, by the local health authorities.
In order to change the situation, the administration of Ganda is working
with the traditional authorities, aiming at taking preventive measures and
sensitizing the population on the basic hygienic care.
